text:
In case people don‚Äôt know Amnesia lore, there are multiple orbs. @1:36:00 Gura asks this question. Agrippa, Alexander and Weyer are all from the other dimension - the same one that Tasi would travel through in Amnesia: Rebirth. They have been living in Prussia for centuries. All of them have been trying to create a traveler‚Äôs locket (or at least a man-made version of it, like a primitive version of Tasi‚Äôs). This is so they can go back to their home world. 

Also, cool easter eggs in both games is those that mention the actual (and historical) French conquest of Algeria took place between 1830 and 1903. There are a couple of notes and writings that are mentioned of this when Gura goes to another area. One being that the French soldiers were in a fort, shooting down the men below whilst they had a ‚Äúmonster‚Äù inside the fort with them. In Rebirth, guess who is in that fort and discovers the soldiers almost 100 years later? Kinda neat with the parallels. Obviously, Rebirth wasn‚Äôt created at the time and it was just The Dark Descent. However, the story of the French soldiers was added as when the conquest of Algeria was going in favor of the French, we hear about English, German and French archaeologists in the 1830s-1860s going into ancient tombs to steal things for their museums back in Europe. Daniel goes with Prof. Herbert on one of these expeditions. Thus, comes into possession of the orb. This then gets mentioned in Rebirth.

Idk, I just think it‚Äôs neat how Frictional Games took the time to tie in parallels to the OG and the direct sequel.

All in all, thank you Gura, for this nostalgic trip.

text:
One problem with nerd culture is it can negatively change your sleep patterns. Long hours sitting, looking at a monitor, stimulating the brain all while intaking at least a days worth of calories and caffeine. 

It's kind of the answer to most stuff but you got to eat less, eat better, and move more. When your body is fully charged it's not going to want to go into sleep mode. Caffeine, even with a high tolerance, will mess with your sleep cycle. Sugar like those in candy bars is just terrible for you overall. 

Computer, TV, and phones give off blue light that is bad for your eyes and tricks your brain into going into wake up mode. Some  computers have "Anti-Blue" modes to help, and there are glasses you can wear to reduce the blue light. I think orange light helps put you in sleep mode. 

Your bedroom should be dark, and the temp should not too hot or cold. Guys tend to like the room a little cooler, and girls like it just a little warmer. The room shouldn't be stuffy or stinky either. Some background white noise like a fan or one of those waterfall things can help too. Try to only use your bed for sleep, and well you know, so your brain isn't going to want to check your phone or play Switch when you're trying to sleep. 

There is also Melatonin. It's an over the counter pill. It's used to help you get asleep, and depending on the pill, stay asleep. People use it if they need to change their sleep times, for jet lag, big day coming up, or just as a general sleep aid. Melatonin is a hormone found in the human body and it regulates sleep-wake cycles. Start with a small dose like 3 or 5, about thirty minutes before bed. It's pretty safe a pills go. The big side effect is more vivid dreams. You can ask your doctor about it. If none of this stuff works you should ask a sleep specialist for help.
